{"id":920,"date":"2012-06-15T10:36:49","date_gmt":"2012-06-15T10:36:49","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/joind.co.uk\/?p=920"},"modified":"2017-02-11T19:57:14","modified_gmt":"2017-02-11T19:57:14","slug":"i-have-had-worse-partings-but-none-that-so-gnaws-at-my-mind-still","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/joind.co.uk\/i-have-had-worse-partings-but-none-that-so-gnaws-at-my-mind-still\/","title":{"rendered":"I have had worse partings, but none that so Gnaws at my mind still"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>There is a grief that runs all the way through motherhood.<\/p>\n<p>The grief in going up to the loft to exchange the 0-3 month old baby-grows for the 3-6 month ones, the grief of withdrawing the breast and saying: &#8220;No more,&#8221; the grief of a child&#8217;s first day in school.<!--more--><\/p>\n<p>It is widely accepted that many parents need to grieve when their children leave home. &#8220;Why wait til then?&#8221; I say.<\/p>\n<p>I have wept over a boy becoming so bonny and chunky he has to be moved from his Moses basket into a cot, over him becoming so independent he no longer finds it necessary to curl my thumb within his hand.<\/p>\n<p>I am grateful to a friend who gave me this poem when I was puzzling over why something as good and natural as a child growing up should also be so poignant.<\/p>\n<p>It \u00a0is the kind of question that only a poet can answer. \u00a0What better answer than this could there be?\u00a0<strong><a href=\"http:\/\/www.bbc.co.uk\/education\/guides\/zx8fbk7\/revision\/8\" target=\"_blank\">Walking Away<\/a><\/strong> by C D-Lewis.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>There is a grief that runs all the way through motherhood. The grief in going up to the loft to exchange the 0-3 month old baby-grows for the 3-6 month ones, the grief of withdrawing the breast and saying: &#8220;No more,&#8221; the grief of a child&#8217;s first day in school.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":2720,"comme